9.	Okay, so we were in Bhubaneshwar for the very first time. While we enjoyed all the beautiful spots it had to offer, we were wandering around to discover a good spot to eat. Hotel Priya came into the picture because it was a continual suggestion on all travel blogs. Finding it was not a big task because its a popular joint. As suggested by all the travel bloggers, we didn't spend much time going through the menu as we were aware of what we needed to order. Hot and Sour Soup - I can't vouch for the sourness but the soup was quite hot. The generous use of Ginger garlic only made it better.
Manchow Soup - We are quite accustomed to a specific taste when it comes to

Manchow Soup. The trouble here was that the soup had a strong tangy flavour of tomato puree rather the punchy flavours of ginger and garlic. We even attempted blending both the soups to compensate for the absence of flavour and the result was surprisingly satisfying.
Masala Dosa - It was reasonably good. The taste transported us back to one of the Udupi joints of Mumbai.
American Corns - It was nothing but corns stir-fried with veggies. Fun to munch along with the main course.
Paneer Pakoda - Large cottage cheese cubes fried in batter. Though a bit bland, dipping it in the hot and sour sauce provided it with the much-required flavour.

Chole Bhature - I guess the restaurant has earned its popularity through this dish. People were endorsing it highly. While I simply loved the Bhature, the chole was a bit flavourless. This left me a bit dissatisfied. Yet the combination of Bhature and sweet curd (which they offered with the chole) was something fresh and exciting.
Final Verdict: It's a good family place with a decent ambience. The service was prompt and welcoming. But I guess that runs in Orissa because everywhere people have greeted us wholeheartedly.

15. When it comes to North Indian food then let's not think of less of oil and butter... those are the key essentials of most of the dishes. Daal Bukhari- It is like our very known Daal Makhani, but it was light and the amount of butter and spices added was just to provide some required flavours to the dish. The best part was that they didn't overdo with the butter to provide that extra rich flavour. Chicken Bharta- The dish was a blend of butter and some fab masalas. The chicken was just perfectly cooked and it wasn't too minced. And that made a difference. It was a nice dish to have with some hot rotis and not that spicy at all. Chicken Tikka Masala- The Reshmi Tikkas were were not dry and were perfectly cooked, they went well with the masalas added to it. Where Chicken Bharta was just about butter and some basic spices; Chicken Tikka Masala was all about that extra richness with a mouthful of flavours! Tawa Naan - They were not only packed well but also cooked in a way that it was all fresh when delivered. And one could enjoy it just the way hot naans are served at the restaurants.

37. One of the age old eatery that has stood the test of time for sure. Located in the heart of kolkata, food lover's paradise Park street boasts of many restaurants, some old some new. Some have been lost to the time and tides, but a few remain as vigilant as ever. The decor is simple but nice with comfortable seats and big tables. The light is not overpowering and the space is quite big. In the soup section their manchow and special soup stood out for me. For starters I would definitely suggest their prawn section like golden fried or pepper and salt. Their rice items are to die for, as are the chicken items like cashew nut chicken and hunan chicken. The bar section has a limited set of common cocktails, but they make up for it with enough options in whisky. If you are interested in checking out their Indian flavours, do try the tandoor section. It is pretty decent although I wouldn't dare say the best in the area. Their chelo kebab has always been a speciality for me and I have always rated it above other joints.

Having frequented this place since childhood and dining atleast once a month during my college days, the only complaint I have ever had was with their front staff. They could be a little bit more courteous in handling customers.

17. Mast Biryani has been able to become a brand in itself for the amazingly delicious biryanis it serves. Located at Zoo Road, this restaurant serves quite many variants of Biryan which are very flavoursome and filling. The place is not very spacious and can host about a dozen and a half people at a time. It is however immaculate and doesn't really give you the feeling of cluttered. For Ambience I'd give it a 3.5/5 Now coming to the food, I have been to this place quite a number of times and have tried their Lucknow Dum Biryani(Chicken), Chicken Kebab Biryani, Shahi Murgh Biryani and Kolkata Dum Biryani. The Lucknow Dum Biryani is my favourite out of them and it is so flavourful that it tantalises your taste buds way too much. The Chicken Kebab Biryani is my second favourite out their, but it is a bit on the spicier side. The Shahi Murg Biryani is an unique take on Biryani and I must admit it's a good take on the Biryani. It's the simple Biryani but with a twist and the twist being the Shahi Murg gravy which is topped upon the biryani handi. The Kolkata Biryani is good too and is a must try. I have also tried their Masala Coke, which had plentiful of chat masala and it is quite refreshing on a hot, humid summer day. The raitas they serve with the Biryanis are however average. But the Biryanis here are a must try. The quantity they serve is very adequate and filling. And also the prices are quite reasonable.

For the food I'd rate them a  The waiters/staff are very welcoming and they do come and they do check if we liked our food and also requests for feedback. Overall they are very courteous and polite. So I'd definitely rate them a 5/5 for service. I can very well bet that no biryani lover have ever been disappointed with this place. If you are a Biryani lover and haven't tried this place yet, then I'd definitely ask you to visit this place once and enjoy their awesomely flavourful and delicious biryani. Trust me, you won't regret. I have always had a good experience with Mast Biryani and I hope they continue to satiate my Biryani cravings wonderfully in the future too.

30. Did you have a hard time craving for some legit Punjabi Cuisines but failing to find a place in Guwahati? Well, worry not coz Rang De Basanti's here for the rescue.

Starting with the interior, the tables been set for twos as well as groups. The milestones placed around reminds you of the National Highways. You'll find some write ups over the walls that'll crack you up. Overall, the place is really nice. Coming to the Food, as soon as you enter, you're served the welcome drinks. For starters and main course, you have the choice of Vegetarian or non-Vegetarian. Out of all the Starter dishes, the Sawa Futiya Seekh was my favourite! Served with some Pudina Chutney, Chilli Chutney and Salad, this 1.25 ft. long mutton kebab was more than just a scrumptious appetizer. My second favourite was the Kambal Fish Tikka. It was fish wrapped in naan and cooked in tandoor, topped with malai, ahaha! So yumm!!! Loved it so much! And my third favourite was the Tangdi"OyeHoye". Now the best aprt about this dish was that it was so delicate that you can easily dig into it using a fork and knife or even with your hands. And taste wise, it was creamy, soft, savoury and overall, very appetizing. The Nachos was fun, very crispy. Coming to the main course, the Panner was soft and it wasn't crumbly, but more like it'd melt in your mouth. The Gravy was smooth, creamy and perfectly spiced. The Keema Kaleji was my favorite. I loved the keema, it was so made to perfection. The Dum Aloo, a vegetarian dish, was simply made with Aloo and regular Indian spices. I really liked the Aloo Matar Pulao. If you wanna have some good rice dish but not much fancy types, you can go for this one. It's simple, it's yummy, tastes good and makes your tummy happy too. The Chicken Bharta was my another favorite. The chicken has been finely shredded and mixed with the Bharta. The onion gives a hint of sweetness, along with the simple spices of the Bharta, really makes it such an amazing dish to have with roti or naan. The Sev Tamatar ki Sabji, made with tomatoes, desi masalas and heaps of besan sev, was the last of the curries that I had. And to have it all with, there are Roti Tokris which consists of Naan, Roti and Paranthas. After all this, if you still have space left in your tummy, you can order something from the Dessert menu. Every dessert tastes delicious.
